    </div>
    <div class="spacer blog-content content-entryindent ">
        "So, boss, how are we tying this together?" Scrap asked as he reached for the salt shaker on the table.  We were at a local deli digesting some wonderful sandwiches, and the morning's events."Lots of suspects, lots of motives, but no smoking gun.  The details of our investigation have been kept pretty close to us throughout, so for the most part nobody knows all the pieces of the puzzle.  This may be an opportunity for us to capitalize on their motive, and their assumption that we're still in the dark on a number of matters." I said with a mouthful of a french dip sandwich.<br/><br/>Scrap took a drink from his water bottle.  "Do I smell another stakeout?" <br/><br/>"Could we be that lucky?" I replied with a grin.  Of course we were going to do another stakeout!<br/><br/>Our plan was formed and agreed upon before our after-lunch coffee cups were cold.  <br/><br/>We returned to Treesoft and initiated our trap.  Scrap spent the next few hours putting together a 'ScrapBag', while I proceeded to interview some remaining staff.  Our plan could only work if certain individuals had no idea that we were on to them. <br/><br/>My interviews left me fruitless, and my last appointment of the day was with Ed, the general counsel of Treesoft.  It was shortly after 1630 hours, and Ed's administrative assistant had gone for the day.<br/><br/>*KNOCK KNOCK*<br/><br/>I tapped on Ed's partially open office door.<br/><br/>"Chief?  Hey, come on in.  Have a seat.  I've been looking forward to our meeting today." Ed said as he shook my paw. <br/><br/>"Thanks for taking the time to see me Ed.  I wanted to update you on our progress.  After our interview with Sven this morning, Scrap and I have developed a plan that I don't want to share with you at this moment.  However, I do need you to explain something to me which may help tie everything together in the end." I stated as I sat down in a plush leather office chair.<br/><br/>Ed grinned from behind his glasses.  "Chief, anything you need.  Just ask.  What can I help you with?" <br/><br/>I pulled a large file folder from my trusty chimp bag and spread the contents over a corner of Ed's desk.<br/><br/>"Ed, this is the standard Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA) that all Treesoft employees are required to sign, along with contractors like Scrap and myself.  Every employee and contractor is given a copy of this agreement, and one copy goes in their employee folder.  However, one employee is missing this agreement from his folder; Eric ManDitt.  Did Eric sign this agreement?" I asked.<br/><br/>Ed immediately turned around in his office chair and started flipping through a filing cabinet.<br/><br/>"You're almost right, Chief.  The employee gets a copy, their file gets a copy, and unknown to the employee is the fact that the legal department keeps a copy too.  Yes, Eric did sign one on his first day of employment.  It's right here." Ed said as he handed me copy of the agreement marred by a large "LEGAL - RECEIVED XX/XX/XX" date stamp at the top of the page.<br/><br/>I grinned.  "Any idea why Eric wouldn't have a copy of the agreement in his file?" <br/><br/>"Well, human resources could have screwed up I suppose.  Or, maybe he removed it without HR knowing?  I'm grasping at straws." Ed replied.<br/><br/>"One other question, Ed.  Can you please explain to me this section of your NDA?" I said, pointing to a paragraph with my right paw.<br/><br/><b>"You acknowledge and agree that due to the unique nature of the Proprietary Information, any breach of this agreement would cause irreparable harm to Company for which damages are not an adequate remedy and that Company shall therefore be entitled to equitable relief in addition to all other remedies available at law." </b><br/><br/>Ed thought for a moment.  "Hmmm.  I have to be honest, this NDA was prepared by our outside legal representation.  What I can tell you is that it was intended to convey the threat of a lawsuit against the breaching party, or possibly the receiving party depending on the situation."<br/><br/>I was writing notes as fast as my monkey arm appendages would push my pen.                                                                               <br/><br/>"We are saying that money wouldn't compensate us.  Unless we can come up with a sum certain amount of damages, assuming we have mitigated any further harm, and the damages were forseeable at the time the contract was formed, we wouldn't be able to bring a breach of contract action anyway." Ed said, appearing a bit perplexed at the wording of the agreement. <br/><br/>My ears were perked.  <br/><br/>"So what you're saying is that you could make a prayer for relief in equity; that relief could be anything from money, to an injunction, to a ..." I asked.<br/><br/>"Yes, yes.  That's what I'm getting at.  It really depends on the situation.  We might sue for damages, we might get an injunction, we might send out cease-and-desist requests.  Can I ask what brought this up?" Ed asked as he pushed his glasses farther back on his nose.<br/><br/>"Just standard review of your agreements." I replied with a grin.<br/><br/>*BEEP*<br/><br/>Scrap had sent me a text message on my trusty Treo.<br/><br/><i>The old lady has dropped her bag.  Film at 11!</i><br/><br/>Nobody can say that Scrap doesn't have a sense of humor.<br/><br/>I thanked Ed for his time and wandered back to our office, closing the door behind me as I entered.<br/><br/>"Did you push the old lady to make her drop her bag?" I asked with a grin.<br/><br/>"You could say that.  The gym bag is on the credenza behind Sven's desk.  I told him I wanted to charge up some laptops, and asked for a power outlet.  I also remembered to lock the bag this time." Scrap said with a grin, remembering a recent case where Scrap's camera equipment was stolen while deployed.<br/><br/>"Fantastic.  If all goes well, we should have some good surveillance to review in about four hours." I said with large smile.<br/><br/>This tree was about to get really constipated.<br/><br/><p><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111101112311/http://www.esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=56592-060317-483055-27"><img alt="esbn" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20111101112311im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/esbnicon.asp?id=5659206031748305527" border="0"> 56592-060317-483055-27</a> Rate content: <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111101112311/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=5659206031748305527&amp;rate=yes"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20111101112311im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbup.gif" border="0"></a><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20111101112311/http://esbn.org/esbn/verify.asp?id=5659206031748305527&amp;rate=no"><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20111101112311im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/thumbdown.gif" border="0"></a><br><img src="https://web.archive.org/web/20111101112311im_/http://esbn.org/esbn/barcode.asp?code=5659206031748305527&amp;height=20&amp;width=1&amp;mode=code39"></p>
    </div>    
    <div class="spacer marginleftgutter">
            <hr/>
    <table width="100%" bgcolor="#FFFFCC" cellpadding="9px">
        <tr>
            <td>
